list.name: [Grid Gen] Prompt Replace
list.description: Replace text in the prompt (or negative prompt) with some other text.

list.name: [Grid Gen] Prompt Add
list.description:
Add text to the end of the prompt in a stackable way.
Only compatible with the base 'prompt' parameter.

list.name: [Grid Gen] Presets
list.description: Apply parameter presets to the image. Can use a comma-separated list to apply multiple per-cell, eg 'a, b || a, c || b, c'

list.name: Prompt
list.description:
The input prompt text that describes the image you want to generate.
Tell the AI what you want to see.
examples: a cartoonish drawing of an astronaut

list.name: Prompt Images
list.description:
Images to include with the prompt, for eg ReVision or UnCLIP.
If this parameter is visible, you've done something wrong - this parameter is tracked internally.

list.name: Negative Prompt
list.description:
Like the input prompt text, but describe what NOT to generate.
Tell the AI things you don't want to see.

list.name: ReVision Strength
list.description:
How strong to apply ReVision image inputs.
Set to 0 to disable ReVision processing.

list.name: ReVision Zero Prompt
list.description:
Zeroes the prompt and negative prompt for ReVision inputs.
Applies only to the base, the refiner will still get prompts.
If you want zeros on both, just delete your prompt text.
If not checked, empty prompts will be zeroed regardless.

list.name: Use Reference Only
list.description:
Use the 'Reference-Only' technique to guide the generation towards the input image.
This currently has side effects that notably prevent Batch from being used properly.

list.name: Images
list.description: How many images to generate at once.

list.name: Seed
list.description:
Image seed.
-1 = random.
Different seeds produce different results for the same prompt.

list.name: Steps
list.description:
Diffusion works by running a model repeatedly to slowly build and then refine an image.
This parameter is how many times to run the model.
More steps = better quality, but more time.
20 is a good baseline for speed, 40 is good for maximizing quality.
Some models, such as Turbo models, are intended for low step counts like 4 or 8.
You can go much higher, but it quickly becomes pointless above 70 or so.
Note that steps is a core parameter used for defining diffusion schedules and other advanced internals,
and merely running the model over top of an existing image is not the same as increasing the steps.
Note that the number of steps actually ran can be influenced by other parameters such as Init Image Creativity when applied.

list.name: CFG Scale
list.description:
How strongly to scale prompt input.
Higher CFG scales tend to produce more contrast, and lower CFG scales produce less contrast.
Too-high values can cause corrupted/burnt images, too-low can cause nonsensical images.
7 is a good baseline. Normal usages vary between 4 and 9.
Some model types, such as Flux, Hunyuan Video, or any Turbo model, expect CFG to be set to 1.

list.name: Text2Video Frames
list.description:
How many frames to generate within the video.
Genmo Mochi 1 can support any frame count up to 200, multiples of 6 plus 1 (7, 13, 19, 25, ...) are required and will automatically round if you enter an invalid value. Defaults to 25.
LTXV supports frame counts anywhere up to 257. Multiples of 8 plus 1 (9, 17, 25, 33, 41, ...) are required and will automatically round if you enter an invalid value. Defaults to 97.
Hunyuan Video and Wan-2.1 support dynamic frame counts. Multiples of 4 plus 1 (5, 9, 13, 17, ...) are required and will automatically round if you enter an invalid value. Hunyuan defaults to 73, Wan defaults to 81.

list.name: Text2Video FPS
list.description:
The FPS (frames per second) to use for video generation.
This configures the target FPS the video is expecting to work at.
For Mochi or Hunyuan Video, this is 24.
For LTXV, 24 fps is native, but other values may work.
For Cosmos, 24 is good but any value from 12 to 40 works.
For Wan, only 16 works.

list.name: Text2Video Boomerang
list.description:
Whether to boomerang (aka pingpong) the video.
If true, the video will play and then play again in reverse to enable smooth looping.

list.name: Text2Video Format
list.description:
What format to save videos in.
Webp video is ideal, but has compatibility issues. Gif is simple and compatible, while gif-hd is higher quality via ffmpeg.
h264-mp4 is a standard video file that works anywhere, but doesn't get treated like an image file.
h265-mp4 is a smaller file size but may not work for all devices.
prores is a specialty format.

list.name: Variation Seed
list.description:
Image-variation seed.
Combined partially with the original seed to create a similar-but-different image for the same seed.
-1 = random.

list.name: Variation Seed Strength
list.description:
How strongly to apply the variation seed.
0 = don't use, 1 = replace the base seed entirely. 0.5 is a good value.

list.name: Aspect Ratio
list.description:
Image aspect ratio - that is, the shape of the image (wide vs square vs tall).
Set to 'Custom' to define a manual width/height instead.
Some models can stretch better than others.
Notably Flux models support almost any resolution you feel like trying.

list.name: Width
list.description:
Image width, in pixels.
SDv1 uses 512, SDv2 uses 768, SDXL prefers 1024.
Some models allow variation within a range (eg 512 to 768) but almost always want a multiple of 64.
Flux is very open to differing values.

list.name: Height
list.description:
Image height, in pixels.
SDv1 uses 512, SDv2 uses 768, SDXL prefers 1024.
Some models allow variation within a range (eg 512 to 768) but almost always want a multiple of 64.
Flux is very open to differing values.

list.name: Side Length
list.description:
Image Side Length, in pixels.
This value is only used with Aspect Ratio not set to 'Custom'.
If unchecked, the model native size is used.
SDv1 uses 512, SDv2 uses 768, SDXL prefers 1024.
Some models allow variation within a range (eg 512 to 768) but almost always want a multiple of 64.
Flux is very open to differing values.

list.name: Cascade Latent Compression
list.description:
How deeply to compress latents when using Stable Cascade.
Default is 32, you can get slightly faster but lower quality results by using 42.

list.name: SD3 TextEncs
list.description:
Which text encoders to use for Stable Diffusion 3 (SD3) models.
Can use CLIP pairs, or T5, or both.
Both is the standard way to run SD3, but CLIP only uses fewer system resources.

list.name: Flux Guidance Scale
list.description:
What guidance scale to use for Flux-Dev or related models.
Does not apply to Flux-Schnell.
For Flux-Dev, this is a distilled embedded value the model was trained on, this is based on an alternative guidance methodology, and is not CFG.
3.5 is default, but closer to 2.0 may allow for more stylistic flexibility.
For Hunyuan Video, this is distilled from CFG Scale, and prefers values closer to 6.

list.name: Flux Disable Guidance
list.description:
Disables Flux Guidance Scale.
Some models prefer this. Usually you don't need this.

list.name: Zero Negative
list.description:
Zeroes the negative prompt if it's empty.
Does nothing if the negative prompt is not empty.
This may yield better quality on SD3.

list.name: Seamless Tileable
list.description:
Makes the generated image seamlessly tileable (like a 3D texture would be).
Optionally, can be tileable on only the X axis (horizontal) or Y axis (vertical).
Only compatible with UNet models (such as SDXL), and not with DiT models (such as Flux).

list.name: Init Image
list.description:
Init-image, to edit an image using diffusion.
This process is sometimes called 'img2img' or 'Image To Image'.

list.name: Init Image Creativity
list.description:
Higher values make the generation more creative, lower values follow the init image closer.
Sometimes referred to as 'Denoising Strength' for 'img2img'.
In simple terms: this is the fraction of steps to actually run, vs steps to pretend already ran.
(Pretending that some steps already ran means the model will act as though it created the image, and only needs to refine the details.
This is how init images function on the inside.)
For example, at Steps=20 and Creativity=0.6, the model will skip the first 8 steps and run the next 12.
If you find your quality is low at low creativity values, it may be beneficial to make your Steps value higher to compensate for this fractional cut.

list.name: Init Image Reset To Norm
list.description:
Merges the init image towards the latent norm.
This essentially lets you boost 'init image creativity' past 1.0.
Set to 0 to disable.

list.name: Init Image Noise
list.description:
Adds non-latent image noise to the Init Image.
This is simple Gaussian noise directly on top of the image.
This tends to encourage more complex/creative generations from diffusion models.
Especially helpful when the init is a flat color reference.
At 0, no noise is added. At 1, heavy noise is added. You can overload up to 10 to more fully hide the source image if needed.

list.name: Mask Image
list.description: Mask-image, white pixels are changed, black pixels are not changed, gray pixels are half-changed.

list.name: Mask Shrink Grow
list.description:
If enabled, the image will be shrunk to just the mask, and then grow by this value many pixels.
After that, the generation process will run in full, and the image will be composited back into the original image at the end.
This allows for refining small details of an image more effectively.
This is also known as 'Inpaint Only Masked'.
Larger values increase the surrounding context the generation receives, lower values contain it tighter and allow the AI to create more detail.

list.name: Mask Blur
list.description:
If enabled, the mask will be blurred by this blur factor.
This makes the transition for the new image smoother.
Set to 0 to disable.

list.name: Mask Grow
list.description:
If enabled, the mask will be grown by this size (approx equivalent to length in pixels).
This helps improve overlap with generated masks.
Set to 0 to disable.

list.name: Init Image Recomposite Mask
list.description:
If enabled and a mask is in use, this will recomposite the masked generated onto the original image for a cleaner result.
If disabled, VAE artifacts may build up across repeated inpaint operations.
Defaults enabled.

list.name: Use Inpainting Encode
list.description:
Uses VAE Encode logic specifically designed for certain inpainting models.
Notably this includes the RunwayML Stable-Diffusion-v1 Inpainting model.
This covers the masked area with gray.

list.name: Unsampler Prompt
list.description:
If enabled, feeds this prompt to an unsampler before resampling with your main prompt.
This is powerful for controlled image editing.

For example, use unsampler prompt 'a photo of a man wearing a black hat',
and give main prompt 'a photo of a man wearing a sombrero', to change what type of hat a person is wearing.

list.name: Refiner Control Percentage
list.description:
Higher values give the refiner more control, lower values give the base more control.
This is similar to 'Init Image Creativity', but for the refiner. This controls how many steps the refiner takes.
In simple terms: this is the fraction of total steps to let the refiner run
For example, at Steps=20 with ControlPercentage=0.2 and Method=PostApply, the base will run 20 steps, then the refiner will run 20*0.2=just 4 steps.
If you find your quality is low at low control percentage values, it may be beneficial to set the advanced Refiner Steps parameter to a very high value let the refine logic run more actual steps.
For example, set RefinerSteps=60 so that 60*0.2=12 steps actually ran in the refiner.

list.name: Refiner Method
list.description:
How to apply the refiner. Different methods create different results.
'PostApply' runs the base in full, then runs the refiner with an Init Image.
'StepSwap' swaps the model after x steps during generation.
'StepSwapNoisy' is StepSwap but with first-stage noise only.

list.name: Refiner Upscale
list.description:
Optional upscale of the image between the base and refiner stage.
Sometimes referred to as 'high-res fix'.
Setting to '1' disables the upscale.

list.name: Refiner Do Tiling
list.description:
If enabled, do generation tiling in the refiner stage.
This can fix some visual artifacts from scaling, but also introduce others (eg seams).
This may take a while to run.
Recommended for SD3 if upscaling.

list.name: Refiner Model
list.description:
The model to use for refinement. This should be a model that's good at small-details, and use a structural model as your base model.
'Use Base' will use your base model rather than switching.
SDXL 1.0 released with an official refiner model.

list.name: Refiner VAE
list.description: Optional VAE replacement for the refiner stage.

list.name: Refiner Steps
list.description:
Alternate Steps value for when calculating the refiner stage.
This replaces the 'Steps' total count before calculating the Refiner Control Percentage.
For example, with Control=0.2, set RefinerSteps=60 so that 60*0.2=12 steps actually ran in the refiner.

list.name: Refiner CFG Scale
list.description:
For the refiner model independently of the base model, how strongly to scale prompt input.
Higher CFG scales tend to produce more contrast, and lower CFG scales produce less contrast.
Too-high values can cause corrupted/burnt images, too-low can cause nonsensical images.
7 is a good baseline. Normal usages vary between 4 and 9.
Some model types, such as Turbo, expect CFG around 1.

list.name: ControlNet Image Input
list.description:
The image to use as the input to ControlNet guidance.
This image will be preprocessed by the chosen preprocessor.
If ControlNet is enabled, but this input is not, Init Image will be used instead.

list.name: ControlNet Model
list.description: The ControlNet model to use.

list.name: ControlNet Strength
list.description: Higher values make the ControlNet apply more strongly. Weaker values let the prompt overrule the ControlNet.

list.name: ControlNet Start
list.description:
When to start applying controlnet, as a fraction of steps.
For example, 0.5 starts applying halfway through. Must be less than End.
Excluding early steps reduces the controlnet's impact on overall image structure.

list.name: ControlNet End
list.description:
When to stop applying controlnet, as a fraction of steps.
For example, 0.5 stops applying halfway through. Must be greater than Start.
Excluding later steps reduces the controlnet's impact on finer details.

list.name: ControlNet Two Image Input
list.description:
The image to use as the input to ControlNet guidance.
This image will be preprocessed by the chosen preprocessor.
If ControlNet is enabled, but this input is not, Init Image will be used instead.

list.name: ControlNet Two Model
list.description: The ControlNet model to use.

list.name: ControlNet Two Strength
list.description: Higher values make the ControlNet apply more strongly. Weaker values let the prompt overrule the ControlNet.

list.name: ControlNet Two Start
list.description:
When to start applying controlnet, as a fraction of steps.
For example, 0.5 starts applying halfway through. Must be less than End.
Excluding early steps reduces the controlnet's impact on overall image structure.

list.name: ControlNet Two End
list.description:
When to stop applying controlnet, as a fraction of steps.
For example, 0.5 stops applying halfway through. Must be greater than Start.
Excluding later steps reduces the controlnet's impact on finer details.

list.name: ControlNet Three Image Input
list.description:
The image to use as the input to ControlNet guidance.
This image will be preprocessed by the chosen preprocessor.
If ControlNet is enabled, but this input is not, Init Image will be used instead.

list.name: ControlNet Three Model
list.description: The ControlNet model to use.

list.name: ControlNet Three Strength
list.description: Higher values make the ControlNet apply more strongly. Weaker values let the prompt overrule the ControlNet.

list.name: ControlNet Three Start
list.description:
When to start applying controlnet, as a fraction of steps.
For example, 0.5 starts applying halfway through. Must be less than End.
Excluding early steps reduces the controlnet's impact on overall image structure.

list.name: ControlNet Three End
list.description:
When to stop applying controlnet, as a fraction of steps.
For example, 0.5 stops applying halfway through. Must be greater than Start.
Excluding later steps reduces the controlnet's impact on finer details.

list.name: ControlNet Preview Only
list.description: (For API usage) If enabled, requests preview output from ControlNet and no image generation at all.

list.name: Video Model
list.description:
The model to use for video generation.
Select an image-to-video conversion model, note that text-to-video models do not work.

list.name: Video Swap Model
list.description: If using a video model pair (eg Wan 2.2) for Image-To-Video, this is the second model to use.

list.name: Video Swap Percent
list.description:
If using a video model pair (eg Wan 2.2), For Image-To-Video, this is the percentage through steps to swap the model at.
Wan 2.2 generally uses 50%.

list.name: Video Frames
list.description:
How many frames to generate within the video.
SVD-XT normally uses 25 frames, and SVD (non-XT) 0.9 used 14 frames.
LTXV supports frame counts anywhere up to 257. Multiples of 8 plus 1 (9, 17, 25, 33, 41, ...) are required and will automatically round if you enter an invalid value. Defaults to 97.
Cosmos was only trained for 121.
Wan 2.1 expects 81, but will mostly work with other values.

list.name: Video Steps
list.description:
How many steps to use for the video model.
Higher step counts yield better quality, but much longer generation time.
20 is sufficient as a basis, but some video models need higher steps to achieve coherence.

list.name: Video CFG
list.description:
The CFG Scale to use for video generation.
With SVD, videos start with this CFG on the first frame, and then reduce to MinCFG (normally 1) by the end frame.
SVD prefers 2.5
Cosmos takes normal CFGs (around 7).
LTXV prefers around 3 for its CFG.
Wan prefers around 6.

list.name: Video Boomerang
list.description:
Whether to boomerang (aka pingpong) the video.
If true, the video will play and then play again in reverse to enable smooth looping.

list.name: Video Resolution
list.description:
What resolution/aspect the video should use.
'Image Aspect, Model Res' uses the aspect-ratio of the image, but the pixel-count size of the model standard resolution.
'Model Preferred' means use the model's exact resolution (eg 1024x576).
'Image' means your input image resolution (ie the standard Resolution parameters control this, usually).

list.name: Video2Video Creativity
list.description:
Optional advanced method to start the video diffusion late.
This is equivalent to Init Image Creativity.
Set below 1 to skip some fraction of steps.
This only makes sense if the base input is a video.
'Video Frame's param must have same frame length as the input video.
If set to 1, video2video logic is not applied, and the input is treated as a single image.

list.name: Video Format
list.description:
What format to save videos in.
Webp video is ideal, but has compatibility issues. Gif is simple and compatible, while gif-hd is higher quality via ffmpeg.
h264-mp4 is a standard video file that works anywhere, but doesn't get treated like an image file.
h265-mp4 is a smaller file size but may not work for all devices.
prores is a specialty format.

list.name: Video End Image
list.description:
An image to use as the 'end frame' of a video.
Only some models support end frames (Wan FLF2V, LTX-V), most don't.

list.name: Video FPS
list.description:
The FPS (frames per second) to use for video generation.
This configures the target FPS the video will try to generate for, or will output as.
Most models are locked to a specific framerate, so altering this is a bad idea.
SVD prefers 6, LTXV prefers 24.

list.name: Video Min CFG
list.description:
The minimum CFG to use for video generation.
Videos start with max CFG on first frame, and then reduce to this CFG. Set to -1 to disable.
Only used for SVD.

list.name: Video Motion Bucket
list.description:
Which trained 'motion bucket' to use for the video model.
Higher values induce more motion. Most values should stay in the 100-200 range.
127 is a good baseline, as it is the most common value in SVD's training set.
Only used for SVD.

list.name: Video Augmentation Level
list.description:
How much noise to add to the init image for Image2Video.
Higher values yield more motion.
For SVD, default is 0.
For LTX, default is 0.15.
Other models do not use this.

list.name: Video Extend Frame Overlap
list.description:
How many frames at the end of the video should be repeated into the start of next video.
This is a balancing act, more frames gets better motion clarity, but also wastes more performance on redundant calculations.
Make sure this is a valid frame count for your video model, eg a multiple of 4 plus 1 for Wan (5, 9, 13, 17, ...).
Should be no more than 1/3rd the frame count of your shortest extend window.

list.name: Video Extend Model
list.description:
The model to use for video extending.
Select an image-to-video model, note that text-to-video models do not work.

list.name: Video Extend Format
list.description:
What format to save extended videos in.
Webp video is ideal, but has compatibility issues. Gif is simple and compatible, while gif-hd is higher quality via ffmpeg.
h264-mp4 is a standard video file that works anywhere, but doesn't get treated like an image file.
h265-mp4 is a smaller file size but may not work for all devices.
prores is a specialty format.

list.name: Model
list.description: What main checkpoint model should be used.

list.name: VAE
list.description:
The VAE (Variational Auto-Encoder) controls the translation between images and latent space.
If your images look faded out, or glitched, you may have the wrong VAE.
All models have a VAE baked in by default, this option lets you swap to a different one if you want to.

list.name: Automatic VAE
list.description:
Whether to automatically select the VAE based on the main model and your user settings.
Only applied if a VAE is not specified.

list.name: LoRAs
list.description:
LoRAs (Low-Rank-Adaptation Models) are a way to customize the content of a model without totally replacing it.
You can enable one or several LoRAs over top of one model.

list.name: LoRA Weights
list.description:
Weight values for the LoRA model list.
Comma separated list of weight numbers.
Must match the length of the LoRAs input.

list.name: LoRA Tenc Weights
list.description:
Distinct weight values for the text encoders of LoRA model list.
Comma separated list of weight numbers.
Must match the length of the LoRAs input.

list.name: LoRA Section Confinement
list.description:
Optional internal parameter used to confine LoRAs to certain sections of generation (eg a 'segment' block).
Comma separated list of section IDs (0 to mean global).
Must match the length of the LoRAs input.

list.name: CLIP-L Model
list.description: Which CLIP-L model to use as a text encoder, for SD3/Flux style 'diffusion_models' folder models.

list.name: CLIP-G Model
list.description: Which CLIP-G model to use as a text encoder, for SD3 style 'diffusion_models' folder models.

list.name: CLIP-Vision Model
list.description: Which CLIP-Vision model to use as an image encoder, for certain image-input tasks.

list.name: T5-XXL Model
list.description: Which T5-XXL model to use as a text encoder, for SD3/Flux style 'diffusion_models' folder models.

list.name: LLaVA Model
list.description: Which LLaVA model to use as a text encoder, for Hunyuan Video 'diffusion_models' folder models.

list.name: LLaMA Model
list.description: Which LLaMA model to use as a text encoder, for HiDream-style 'diffusion_models' folder models.

list.name: Qwen Model
list.description: Which Qwen LLM to use as a text encoder, for OmniGen/QwenImage-style 'diffusion_models' folder models.

list.name: Torch Compile
list.description:
Torch.Compile is a way to dynamically accelerate AI models.
It wastes a bit of time (around a minute) on the first call compiling a graph of the generation, and then all subsequent generations run faster thanks to the compiled graph.
Torch.Compile depends on Triton, which is difficult to install on Windows, easier on Linux.

list.name: Override Prediction Type
list.description:
Override the prediction type set in the model.
This is almost never a good idea to touch.

list.name: Batch Size
list.description:
Batch size - generates more images at once on a single GPU.
This increases VRAM usage.
May in some cases increase overall speed by a small amount (runs slower to get the images, but slightly faster per-image).

list.name: Alt Resolution Height Multiplier
list.description: When enabled, the normal width parameter is used, and this value is multiplied by the width to derive the image height.

list.name: Raw Resolution
list.description:
Optional advanced way to manually specify raw resolutions, useful for grids.
When enabled, this overrides the default width/height params.

list.name: Output Intermediate Images
list.description:
If checked, intermediate images (eg before a refiner or segment stage) will be output separately alongside the final image.
If unchecked, only the final image will be output.

list.name: Do Not Save
list.description:
If checked, tells the server to not save this image.
Useful for quick test generations, or 'generate forever' usage.

list.name: Do Not Save Intermediates
list.description:
If checked, tells the server to that intermediate files should not be saved to file.
They will still appear in your batch view, just not stored permanently.

list.name: No Previews
list.description:
If checked, tells the server that previews are not desired.
May make generations slightly faster in some cases.

list.name: Webhooks
list.description: What webhooks are enabled for this generation job.
value_names: Manual (fire 'Every Gen' and 'Manual' for each image)
Manual At End (fire 'Every Gen', then one 'Manual' for the full set of queued gens)

list.name: [Internal] Backend Type
list.description: Which SwarmUI backend type should be used for this request.

list.name: Exact Backend ID
list.description: Manually force a specific exact backend (by ID #) to be used for this generation.

list.name: Wildcard Seed
list.description:
Wildcard selection seed.
If enabled, this seed will be used for selecting entries from wildcards.
If disabled, the image seed will be used.
-1 = random.

list.name: Wildcard Seed Behavior
list.description:
How Wildcard Seed should behave.
If 'Random', seed is a random seed.
If 'Index', the seed is a 0-based index into the wildcard list. (Eg if you have 5 entries, seed 0 gets the first entry, seed 4 gets the last entry, seed 5 goes back to the first entry again.)

list.name: No Seed Increment
list.description:
If checked, the seed will not be incremented when Images is above 1.
Useful for example to test different wildcards for the same seed rapidly.

list.name: Personal Note
list.description:
Optional field to type in any personal text note you want.
This will be stored in the image metadata.

list.name: Image Format
list.description: Optional override for the final image file format.

list.name: Color Depth
list.description:
Specifies the color depth (in bits per channel) to use.
Only works for 'PNG' image file format currently.
'8-bit' is normal (8 bits per red, 8 for green, 8 for blue, making 24 bits total per pixel).
and '16-bit' encodes additional high-precision (HDR-like) data.
Note that overprecision data is unlikely to be meaningful, as currently available models haven't been trained for that.

list.name: Override Outpath Format
list.description: Override the Outpath-Format user setting. Full details in the docs here.

list.name: Model Specific Enhancements
list.description:
If checked, enables model-specific enhancements.
For example, on SDXL, smarter res-cond will be used.
If unchecked, will prefer more 'raw' behavior.

list.name: [FreeU] Apply To
list.description: Which models to apply FreeU to, as base, refiner, or both. Irrelevant when not using refiner.

list.name: [FreeU] Version
list.description:
Which version of FreeU to use.
1 is the version in the original paper, 2 is a variation of it developed by the same original author of FreeU.

list.name: [FreeU] Block One
list.description:
Block1 multiplier value for FreeU.
Paper recommends 1.1.

list.name: [FreeU] Block Two
list.description:
Block2 multiplier value for FreeU.
Paper recommends 1.2.

list.name: [FreeU] Skip One
list.description:
Skip1 multiplier value for FreeU.
Paper recommends 0.9.

list.name: [FreeU] Skip Two
list.description:
Skip2 multiplier value for FreeU.
Paper recommends 0.2.

list.name: Global Region Factor
list.description:
When using regionalized prompts, this factor controls how strongly the global prompt overrides the regional prompts.
0 means ignore global prompt, 1 means ignore regional, 0.5 means half-n-half.

list.name: Regional Object Cleanup Factor
list.description:
When using an 'object' prompt, how much to cleanup the end result by.
This is the 'init image creativity' of the final cleanup step.
Set to 0 to disable.

list.name: Regional Object Inpainting Model
list.description: When using regionalized prompts with distinct 'object' values, this overrides the model used to inpaint those objects.

list.name: Mask Composite Unthresholded
list.description:
If checked, when masks are recomposited (eg from a '<segment:>'), it will be recomposited with the exact raw mask.
If false, it will boolean threshold the mask first.
The boolean threshold is 'more correct' and leads to better content replacement, whereas disabling threshold (by checking this option) may lead to better looking refinements.

list.name: Save Segment Mask
list.description: If checked, any usage of '<segment:>' syntax in prompts will save the generated mask in output.

list.name: Segment Mask Blur
list.description:
Amount of blur to apply to the segment mask before using it.
This is for '<segment:>' syntax usage.
Defaults to 10.

list.name: Segment Mask Grow
list.description:
Number of pixels of grow the segment mask by.
This is for '<segment:>' syntax usage.
Defaults to 16.

list.name: Segment Mask Oversize
list.description:
How wide a segment mask should be oversized by.
Larger values include more context to get more accurate inpaint,
and smaller values get closer to get better details.

list.name: Segment Threshold Max
list.description:
Maximum mask match value of a segment before clamping.
Lower values force more of the mask to be counted as maximum masking.
Too-low values may include unwanted areas of the image.
Higher values may soften the mask.

list.name: Segment Sort Order
list.description:
How to sort segments when using '<segment:yolo->' syntax with indices.
For example: <segment:yolo-face_yolov8m-seg_60.pt-2> with largest-smallest, will select the second largest face segment.

list.name: Segment Target Resolution
list.description:
Optional specific target resolution for segment.
This controls both aspect ratio, and size.
This is just a target, the system may fail to exactly hit it.
If the mask is on the edge of an image, the aspect may be squished.
If unspecified, the aspect ratio of the detection will be used, and the resolution of the model.

list.name: Segment Model
list.description: Optionally specify a distinct model to use for 'segment' values.

list.name: Segment Steps
list.description:
Alternate Steps value for when calculating the segment stage.
This replaces the 'Steps' total count before calculating the Segment Creativity.

list.name: Segment CFG Scale
list.description:
For the segment model independently of the base model, how strongly to scale prompt input.
Higher CFG scales tend to produce more contrast, and lower CFG scales produce less contrast.
Too-high values can cause corrupted/burnt images, too-low can cause nonsensical images.
7 is a good baseline. Normal usages vary between 4 and 9.
Some model types, such as Turbo, expect CFG around 1.

list.name: Sampler Sigma Min
list.description:
Minimum sigma value for the sampler.
Only applies to Karras/Exponential schedulers.

list.name: Sampler Sigma Max
list.description:
Maximum sigma value for the sampler.
Only applies to Karras/Exponential schedulers.

list.name: Sigma Shift
list.description:
Sigma shift is used for modern rectified flow models (like SD3) specifically.
This shifts the balance of steps between low-frequency steps (structural/compositional steps), and high-frequency steps (detail steps).
This value only works within ranges a model was trained for, so for most models you should leave this param disabled to use the default, but fiddling it can sometimes work to adjust results.
For SD3, this value is recommended to be in the range of 1.5 to 3, normally 3.
For AuraFlow, 1.73 (square root of 3) is recommended.
For Flux, Schnell uses 0, 1.15 may be good for Dev.
HiDream uses 3, but HiDream Dev also likes 6.

list.name: Sampler Rho
list.description:
Rho value for the sampler.
Only applies to Karras/Exponential schedulers.

list.name: IP2P CFG 2
list.description: CFG Scale for Cond2-Negative in InstructPix2Pix (Edit) models.

list.name: CLIP Stop At Layer
list.description:
What layer of CLIP to stop at, from the end.
Also known as 'CLIP Skip'. Default CLIP Skip is -1 for SDv1, some models prefer -2.
SDv2, SDXL, and beyond do not need this set ever.

list.name: VAE Tile Size
list.description:
If enabled, decodes images through the VAE using tiles of this size.
VAE Tiling reduces VRAM consumption, but takes longer and may impact quality.

list.name: VAE Tile Overlap
list.description:
If VAE Tile Size is enabled, this controls how much overlap between tiles there should be.
Higher overlap improves quality but takes longer.

list.name: VAE Temporal Tile Size
list.description:
If VAE Tile Size is enabled, decodes videos through the VAE using video frame tiles of this size.
VAE Tiling reduces VRAM consumption, but takes longer and may impact quality.

list.name: VAE Temporal Tile Overlap
list.description:
If VAE Tile Size is enabled, this controls how much overlap between video frames there should be.
Higher overlap improves quality but takes longer.

list.name: Color Correction Behavior
list.description:
Experimental: How to correct color when compositing a masked image.
'None' = Do not attempt color correction.
'Uniform' = Compute a fixed offset HSV correction for all pixels.
'Linear' = Compute a linear correction that depends on each pixel's S and V.
'Linear2' = experimental improvement to regular Linear that seems better.
This is useful for example when doing inpainting with Flux models, as the Flux VAE does not retain consistent colors - 'Linear2' may help correct for this misbehavior.

list.name: Remove Background
list.description:
If enabled, removes the background from the generated image.
This internally uses RemBG.

list.name: End Steps Early
list.description: Percentage of steps to cut off before the image is done generation.

list.name: Mask Behavior
list.description:
How to process the mask, for masked-generation such as Init Image with a Mask Image, or Segment blocks.
'Differential' = 'Differential Diffusion' technique, wherein the mask values are used as offsets for timestep of when to apply the mask or not.
'Simple Latent' = the most basic latent masking technique.

list.name: Trim Video Start Frames
list.description:
Trim this many frames from the start of a video output.
This will shorten a video, and is just a fix for video models that corrupt start frames (such as Wan).

list.name: Trim Video End Frames
list.description:
Trim this many frames from the end of a video output.
This will shorten a video, and is just a fix for video models that corrupt end frames (such as Wan).

list.name: Placeholder Param - Group Starred
list.description: Placeholder hidden parameter to make the 'Starred' Group exist.

list.name: Placeholder Param - Group User One
list.description: Placeholder hidden parameter to make the 'User Group 1' Group exist.

list.name: Placeholder Param - Group User Two
list.description: Placeholder hidden parameter to make the 'User Group 2' Group exist.

list.name: Placeholder Param - Group User Three
list.description: Placeholder hidden parameter to make the 'User Group 3' Group exist.

list.name: Automatic Scorer
list.description: Scoring engine(s) to use when scoring this image. Multiple scorers can be used and will be averaged together. Scores are saved in image metadata.

list.name: Score Must Exceed
list.description: Only keep images with a generated score above this minimum.

list.name: Take Best N Score
list.description:
Only keep the best *this many* images in a batch based on scoring.
(For example, if batch size = 8, and this value = 2, then 8 images will generate and will be scored, and the 2 best will be kept and the other 6 discarded.)

list.name: [DT] Mimic Scale
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
Mimic Scale value (target for the CFG Scale recentering).

list.name: [DT] Threshold Percentile
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
thresholding percentile. '1' disables, '0.95' is decent value for enabled.

list.name: [DT] CFG Scale Mode
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
Mode for the CFG Scale scheduler.

list.name: [DT] CFG Scale Minimum
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
CFG Scale minimum value (for non-constant CFG mode).

list.name: [DT] Mimic Scale Mode
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
Mode for the Mimic Scale scheduler.

list.name: [DT] Mimic Scale Minimum
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
Mimic Scale minimum value (for non-constant mimic mode).

list.name: [DT] Scheduler Value
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
If either scale scheduler is 'Power', this is the power factor.
If using 'repeating', this is the number of repeats per image. Otherwise, it does nothing.

list.name: [DT] Separate Feature Channels
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
Whether to separate the feature channels.
Normally leave this on. I think it should be off for RCFG?

list.name: [DT] Scaling Startpoint
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
Whether to scale relative to the mean value or to zero.
Use 'MEAN' normally. If you want RCFG logic, use 'ZERO'.

list.name: [DT] Variability Measure
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
Whether to use standard deviation ('STD') or thresholded absolute values ('AD').
Normally use 'AD'. Use 'STD' if wanting RCFG logic.

list.name: [DT] Interpolate Phi
list.description:
[Dynamic Thresholding]
'phi' interpolation factor.
Interpolates between original value and DT value, such that 0.0 = use original, and 1.0 = use DT.
(This exists because RCFG is bad and so half-removing it un-breaks it - better to just not do RCFG).

list.name: Use IP-Adapter
list.description: Select an IP-Adapter model to use IP-Adapter for image-prompt input handling. Models will automatically be downloaded when you first use them. Note if you use a custom model, you must also set your ReVision Model under Advanced Model Addons, otherwise CLIP Vision G will be presumed. See more docs here.

list.name: IP-Adapter Weight
list.description: Weight to use with IP-Adapter (if enabled).

list.name: IP-Adapter Start
list.description:
When to start applying IP-Adapter, as a fraction of steps (if enabled).
For example, 0.25 starts applying a quarter (25%) of the way through. Must be less than IP-Adapter End.

list.name: IP-Adapter End
list.description:
When to stop applying IP-Adapter, as a fraction of steps (if enabled).
For example, 0.5 stops applying halfway (50%) through. Must be greater than IP-Adapter Start.

list.name: IP-Adapter Weight Type
list.description:
How to shift the weighting of the IP-Adapter.
This can produce subtle but useful different effects.

list.name: Use Style Model
list.description:
Select a Style model to use it for image-prompt input handling.
Flux.1 Redux is an example of a style model.
Place these models in `(Swarm)/Models/style_models`.

list.name: Style Model Merge Strength
list.description:
How strongly to merge in the effects of the style model.
At 1, the style model is fully used.
At 0, the style model is ignored.
For Flux Redux, very low values (eg 0.1) are recommended.

list.name: Style Model Multiply Strength
list.description:
How strongly to multiply the effects of the style model.
At 1, the style model is fully used.
At 0, the style model is ignored.
For Flux Redux, very low values (eg 0.1) are recommended.

list.name: Style Model Apply Start
list.description:
When to start applying the Style Model, as a fraction of steps (if enabled).
For example, 0.25 starts applying a quarter (25%) of the way through.
This is probably off-scale due to scheduler behavior in ComfyUI internals. Very low values are recommend for practical usage.

list.name: [ComfyUI] Custom Workflow
list.description:
What custom workflow to use in ComfyUI (built in the Comfy Workflow Editor tab).
Generally, do not use this directly.

list.name: Sampler
list.description:
Sampler type (for ComfyUI backends).
Generally, 'Euler' is fine, but for SD1 and SDXL 'DPM++ 2M' is popular when paired with the 'Karras' scheduler.
'Ancestral' and 'SDE' samplers only work with non-rectified models (eg SD1/SDXL) and randomly move over time.
Some special model variants require specific Samplers or Schedulers.
'CFG++' samplers have a different CFG range than normal (between 0 to 2, depending).
value_names: DPM Fast (DPM without the DPM2 slowdown)
DDIM (Denoising Diffusion Implicit Models) (Identical to Euler)
iPNDM (Improved Pseudo-Numerical methods for Diffusion Models)
SEEDS 2 (Exponential SDE Solvers, variant of DPM++ SDE)

list.name: Scheduler
list.description:
Scheduler type (for ComfyUI backends).
Goes with the Sampler parameter above.

list.name: Enable AITemplate
list.description: If checked, enables AITemplate for ComfyUI generations (UNet only). Only compatible with some GPUs.

list.name: Preferred DType
list.description:
Preferred data type for models, when a choice is available.
(Notably primarily affects Flux.1 models currently).
If disabled, will automatically decide.
'fp8_e43fn' is recommended for large models.
'Default' uses global default type, usually fp16 or bf16.

list.name: Self-Attention Guidance Scale
list.description:
Scale for Self-Attention Guidance.
''Self-Attention Guidance (SAG) uses the intermediate self-attention maps of diffusion models to enhance their stability and efficacy.
Specifically, SAG adversarially blurs only the regions that diffusion models attend to at each iteration and guides them accordingly.''
Defaults to 0.5.
This is only expected to work on older unet-based models (eg SDXL) and not on newer models.

list.name: Self-Attention Guidance Sigma Blur
list.description:
Blur-sigma for Self-Attention Guidance.
Defaults to 2.0.

list.name: Perturbed-Attention Guidance Scale
list.description:
Scale for Perturbed-Attention Guidance (PAG).
''PAG is designed to progressively enhance the structure of synthesized samples throughout the denoising process by considering the self-attention mechanisms' ability to capture structural information.
It involves generating intermediate samples with degraded structure by substituting selected self-attention maps in diffusion U-Net with an identity matrix, and guiding the denoising process away from these degraded samples.''
Defaults to 3.
This is only expected to work on older unet-based models (eg SDXL) and not on newer models.

list.name: Rescale CFG Multiplier
list.description:
If enabled, use Comfy's native version of RescaleCFG.
This is only expected to work on certain vpred models.
This is, generally, pointless.
The value specified is the multiplier rate.

list.name: Renorm CFG
list.description:
If enabled, use 'Renorm CFG', a technique developed for use with Lumina 2.
At 0, this does nothing. Lumina 2 reference code sets this to 1.
This parameter only works on some models, and will corrupt others.

list.name: Use CFG Zero Star
list.description: If enabled, use 'CFG Zero Star' (CFG-Zero*, defined in this paper). This may slightly improve quality on modern 'Flow' models when using CFG.

list.name: Refiner Upscale Method
list.description: How to upscale the image, if upscaling is used.

list.name: Refiner Sampler
list.description:
Sampler type (for ComfyUI backends).
Generally, 'Euler' is fine, but for SD1 and SDXL 'DPM++ 2M' is popular when paired with the 'Karras' scheduler.
'Ancestral' and 'SDE' samplers only work with non-rectified models (eg SD1/SDXL) and randomly move over time.
Some special model variants require specific Samplers or Schedulers.
'CFG++' samplers have a different CFG range than normal (between 0 to 2, depending).
This is an override to only affect the Refine/Upscale stage.
value_names: DPM Fast (DPM without the DPM2 slowdown)
DDIM (Denoising Diffusion Implicit Models) (Identical to Euler)
iPNDM (Improved Pseudo-Numerical methods for Diffusion Models)
SEEDS 2 (Exponential SDE Solvers, variant of DPM++ SDE)

list.name: Refiner Scheduler
list.description:
Scheduler type (for ComfyUI backends).
Goes with the Sampler parameter above.
This is an override to only affect the Refine/Upscale stage.

list.name: ControlNet Preprocessor
list.description:
The preprocessor to use on the ControlNet input image.
If toggled off, will be automatically selected.
Use 'None' to disable preprocessing.

list.name: ControlNet Union Type
list.description: For Union ControlNets, you can optionally manually specify the union controlnet type.

list.name: ControlNet Two Preprocessor
list.description:
The preprocessor to use on the ControlNet input image.
If toggled off, will be automatically selected.
Use 'None' to disable preprocessing.

list.name: ControlNet Two Union Type
list.description: For Union ControlNets, you can optionally manually specify the union controlnet type.

list.name: ControlNet Three Preprocessor
list.description:
The preprocessor to use on the ControlNet input image.
If toggled off, will be automatically selected.
Use 'None' to disable preprocessing.

list.name: ControlNet Three Union Type
list.description: For Union ControlNets, you can optionally manually specify the union controlnet type.

list.name: Debug Regional Prompting
list.description: If checked, outputs masks from regional prompting for debug reasons.

list.name: Refiner HyperTile
list.description:
The size of hypertiles to use for the refining stage.
HyperTile is a technique to speed up sampling of large images by tiling the image and batching the tiles.
This is useful when using SDv1 models as the refiner. SDXL-Base models do not benefit as much.

list.name: Text2Video Frame Interpolation Multiplier
list.description:
How many frames to interpolate between each frame in the video.
Higher values are smoother, but make take significant time to save the output, and may have quality artifacts.

list.name: Text2Video Frame Interpolation Method
list.description:
How to interpolate frames in the video.
'RIFE' or 'FILM' are two different decent interpolation model options.

list.name: Video Preview Type
list.description:
How to display previews for generating videos.
'Animate' shows a low-res animated video preview.
'iterate' shows one frame at a time while it goes.
'one' displays just the first frame.
'none' disables previews.

list.name: Video Frame Interpolation Multiplier
list.description:
How many frames to interpolate between each frame in the video.
Higher values are smoother, but make take significant time to save the output, and may have quality artifacts.

list.name: Video Frame Interpolation Method
list.description:
How to interpolate frames in the video.
'RIFE' or 'FILM' are two different decent interpolation model options.

list.name: GLIGEN Model
list.description:
Optionally use a GLIGEN model.
GLIGEN is only compatible with SDv1 at time of writing.

list.name: Shifted Latent Average Init
list.description:
If checked, shifts the empty latent to use a mean-average per-channel latent value (as calculated by Birchlabs).
If unchecked, default behavior of zero-init latents are used.
This can potentially improve the color range or even general quality on SDv1, SDv2, and SDXL models.
Note that the effect is very minor.

list.name: YOLO Model Internal
list.description:
Parameter for internally tracking YOLOv8 models.
This is not for real usage, it is just to expose the list to the UI handler.

list.name: TeaCache Mode
list.description: When to use TeaCache. TeaCache is a trick to accelerate diffusion models, especially video models. That is: generation runs faster, but loses some quality. See here for more info. You can leave this disabled, enabled for all model sampling stages, or only enabled for certain model sampling stages. (This separation is so eg you can accelerate your video generation, without losing quality of an initial image).
value_names: base gen only (no refiner or video)

list.name: TeaCache Threshold
list.description:
What threshold to use with TeaCache.
See 'TeaCache Mode' parameter above.
0.4 might work well with Flux image generation, and 0.15 might work well with video generation.
0.25 is a good stable default for most purposes - decent acceleration but little visual change.

list.name: TeaCache Start
list.description:
When to start applying TeaCache, as a fraction of steps (if enabled).
0 is the recommended default for most models.
Comfy-TeaCache node pack author recommends a slightly higher setting for some models (eg 0.1 for some Wan variants and HiDream Full, never above 0.2).

list.name: Nunchaku Cache Threshold
list.description:
What threshold to use with Nunchaku block caching.
This makes Nunchaku gens faster at the cost of quality.
Only applicable to Nunchaku models.
Generally 0 to 0.2 is the reasonable range, above that you can start noticing quality drop.

list.name: Set CLIP Device
list.description: Override the hardware device that text encoders run on.

list.name: [AutoWebUI] Sampler
list.description: Sampler type (for AutoWebUI)

groups.name: Image Prompting
groups.description: Image prompting with ReVision, IP-Adapter, etc. See more docs here.

groups.name: Starred
groups.description: User-selectable starred parameters, brought to the top of the parameter list for convenient access.

groups.name: Variation Seed
groups.description:
Variation Seeds let you reuse a single seed, but slightly vary it according to a second seed and a weight value.
This technique results in creating images that are almost the same, but with small variations.
Using two static seeds and adjusting the strength can produce a smooth transition between two seeds.

groups.name: Init Image
groups.description:
Init-image, to edit an image using diffusion.
This process is sometimes called 'img2img' or 'Image To Image'.

groups.name: Refine / Upscale
groups.description:
This group contains everything related to two-stage image generation.
Notably this includes post-refinement, step-swap refinement, and upscaled refinement.
Upscaling an image and refining with the same model has been referred to as 'hires fix' in other UIs.

groups.name: ControlNet
groups.description: Guide your image generations with ControlNets. See more docs here.

groups.name: ControlNet Two
groups.description: Guide your image generations with ControlNets. See more docs here.

groups.name: ControlNet Three
groups.description: Guide your image generations with ControlNets. See more docs here.

groups.name: Image To Video
groups.description: Generate videos with Stable Video Diffusion. See more docs here.

groups.name: Advanced Video
groups.description: Advanced/special Video model features that only apply to some video models.

groups.name: FreeU
groups.description: Implements 'FreeU: Free Lunch in Diffusion U-Net' This is a minor adjustment to legacy Unet models (eg SDv1, SDXL). It does not apply to newer DiT models, and even for Unet models it's not recommended.

groups.name: Scoring
groups.description:
The Scorers extension implements automatic image scoring, useful for eg Grid Generator usage to automatically rate the grid.
This is a legacy implementation pending a rewrite. Most users should not use this.

groups.name: Refiner Param Overrides
groups.description: This sub-group of the Refine/Upscale group contains core-parameter overrides, such as replacing the base Step count or CFG Scale, unique to the refine/upscale generation stage.

groups.name: Segment Param Overrides
groups.description: This sub-group of the Segmentation group contains core-parameter overrides, such as replacing the base Step count or CFG Scale, unique to the segment generation stage.

groups.name: Alternate Guidance
groups.description:
Alternative guidance methods.
These replace CFG or sampling with alternative systems that claim to yield better results.
These are often highly contextual (eg work on some models but not others), and can be known to add more trouble than they're worth.
These generally cannot stack: pick one to use, not multiple, unless documented otherwise.
